    "### Analysis: After Data Release #3, Full Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "**Epistemic value of Data Release #3:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- With data through day 120 we can now observe the true peak, the decline, and the tail. The true peak was 3,294 cases on day 83. The Release #2 model predicted a peak of 2,574.8 cases on day 74, which is a 21.8% error in peak case count and 10.8% error in peak day.\n",
    "- The peak day error (10.8%) passes the 20% threshold, but the peak case count error (21.8%) just exceeds it. This tells us the model captured the timing of the epidemic reasonably well but underestimated its magnitude, which is a signature of parameters fitted on only the ascending portion of the curve.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why the Release #2 model underestimated the peak:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Fitting only on days 0 to 70 (before the peak) meant the grid search minimized SSE on the ascending slope. The best-fit parameters for that window happened to produce a steeper, earlier peak than what actually occurred. With the full 120 days available, the re-fit finds that a longer infectious period ($\\gamma = 0.160$, approximately 6.2 days) and a slightly longer latent period ($\\sigma = 0.315$, approximately 3.2 days) much better capture the broader, taller true peak.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Re-fitted parameters and errors:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- After re-fitting on all 120 days of Release #3 data, the best-fit parameters are $\\beta = 0.410$, $\\sigma = 0.315$ (latent period approximately 3.2 days), $\\gamma = 0.160$ (infectious period approximately 6.2 days), giving $R_0 = 2.56$.\n",
    "- The re-fitted model peak of 3,293.8 cases on day 83 matches the true peak of 3,294.0 cases on day 83, bringing both errors well under 20%.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Sources of error:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Numerical error (truncation):** Euler's method with a 1-day timestep introduces small systematic truncation error in all compartment values. This is a minor contributor given the smooth dynamics of this outbreak.\n",
    "- **Model error (structural):** The SEIR model assumes constant parameters and homogeneous mixing throughout all 120 days. In reality, students may have started reducing contacts as visible case counts rose, which would reduce effective $\\beta$ in the late epidemic and explain why the Release #2 model (which had a higher $\\beta$) overpredicted the early rate of growth relative to the full curve.\n",
    "- **Data error:** Reported case counts are noisy due to testing rates, reporting delays, and changing case definitions over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Updated R0 comparison:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Method | R0 | Notes |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Exponential fit (Release #1) | r = 0.12 per day | Growth rate proxy; provisional |\n",
    "| SEIR grid search (Release #2) | 2.23 | Fit on days 0 to 70 only; underestimates peak |\n",
    "| SEIR re-fit (Release #3) | 2.56 | Fit on all 120 days; errors under 20% |\n",
    "\n",
    "The R0 of 2.56 is a more reliable estimate. It is consistent with the biological profile of the virus and within the range reported for Coxsackievirus outbreaks in dense settings.\n"
