    "### Analysis: Intervention Strategies at Virginia Tech\n",
    "\n",
    "**A note on the two effectiveness metrics in the table:**\n",
    "\n",
    "The summary table reports two measures of intervention effectiveness. \"Active case-days prevented\" is the difference in the total area under the I(t) curves between the no-intervention scenario and the intervention. It sums up how many people were infectious on each day and takes the difference, so it can easily exceed N because it counts each day of each infection separately, not unique individuals. \"Cases prevented (approx)\" divides the case-days by the baseline infectious period (1/$\\gamma$ = 6.25 days), converting the area reduction into an approximate count of unique infections averted. This is the more intuitive number and is bounded by N.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Expected epidemic dynamics at VT vs. UVA:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- With the same per-contact parameters ($\\beta = 0.410$, $\\sigma = 0.315$, $\\gamma = 0.160$) but a larger population (N = 39,000 vs. 20,000), VT's outbreak follows a qualitatively similar trajectory but reaches substantially higher absolute case counts and a later peak.\n",
    "- Without any intervention, the VT model predicts a peak of 6,418.9 active cases on day 89 and 720.8 active cases still remaining at day 120.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Comparison across intervention strategies:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Testing and Quarantine (Int 4)** is by far the most effective single intervention: it prevents approximately 29,317 unique cases (183,230 case-days / 6.25 days) and brings active infections to near zero by day 120. Increasing $\\gamma$ compresses the infectious period from approximately 6.2 days to approximately 1.5 days, dramatically cutting each person's transmission window and the total area under the I(t) curve.\n",
    "- **School Closure (Int 5)** prevents approximately 11,392 unique cases (71,202 case-days / 6.25 days), but leaves 3,718.9 active cases at day 120, the highest of all interventions. The two-week reduction in $\\beta$ delays the peak from day 89 to day 115, but the epidemic rebounds sharply once schools reopen. Without a sustained follow-on measure, closure only shifts the problem later.\n",
    "- **Masking (Int 1)** prevents approximately 10,904 unique cases (68,153 case-days / 6.25 days) and reduces the peak to 3,233.3 cases on day 85. It is slightly less effective than school closure in total case-days, but far better at day 120 (1,102.8 vs. 3,718.9 active cases), because the sustained reduction in $\\beta$ continues to suppress transmission after the peak.\n",
    "- **Vaccine interventions (Int 2 and Int 3)** prevent approximately 2,206 and 2,701 unique cases respectively, meaningfully less than the behavioral interventions. Only 1,800 to 2,700 effective immunizations are applied to a population of 39,000 with substantial ongoing transmission, limiting their population-level impact.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Modeling process awareness and limitations:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The unique cases estimate divides by the baseline $\\gamma$ for all interventions as a consistent denominator. For Int 4 specifically, the effective infectious period is shorter (because $\\gamma$ is increased), which means the case-days prevented figure underestimates the actual cases averted relative to what you would compute from the compartment outputs directly. The approximation is still useful for comparing interventions on an intuitive scale.\n",
    "- These intervention models assume immediate and 100% compliant behavior change at day 70. In practice, real-world benefits will be somewhat lower than simulated.\n",
    "- The school closure rebound at day 120 (3,718.9 active cases) is particularly notable here because the longer infectious period means the epidemic sustains much longer after reopening. Closure without a follow-on strategy is especially risky in this parameter regime.\n"
