    "## Recommendations for Virginia Tech\n",
    "\n",
    "Based on our SEIR modeling of five intervention strategies beginning at day 70 of the VT outbreak (N = 39,000, parameters from the Release #3 re-fit: $\\beta = 0.410$, $\\sigma = 0.315$, $\\gamma = 0.160$), the following recommendations are ordered by projected unique cases prevented (case-days prevented divided by the baseline infectious period of 6.25 days).\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. Testing and Quarantine, Strongly Recommended as Primary Intervention\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Modeled effect:** Approximately 29,317 unique cases prevented (183,230 case-days / 6.25 days); drives active infections to approximately 1 case by day 120.\n",
    "- **Mechanism:** Increases the effective recovery rate ($\\gamma$) by identifying and isolating infectious individuals early, compressing the infectious period from approximately 6.2 days to approximately 1.5 days.\n",
    "- **Implementation target:** Rapid testing turnaround (under 48 hours from symptom onset), with immediate quarantine of confirmed cases and close contacts.\n",
    "- **Trade-offs:** Resource-intensive; requires sufficient testing infrastructure, isolation housing, and compliance incentives. Equity concern: students without private housing or paid sick leave may face disproportionate burden.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Masking Mandate, Recommended as Sustained Complement\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Modeled effect:** Approximately 10,904 unique cases prevented (68,153 case-days / 6.25 days); reduces peak from 6,418.9 to 3,233.3 cases and leaves 1,102.8 active cases at day 120.\n",
    "- **Mechanism:** Reduces $\\beta$ by 40% indefinitely, as long as compliance holds.\n",
    "- **Advantage over closure:** The masking benefit persists past the intervention window and does not produce a rebound. Day-120 active cases under masking (1,102.8) are far lower than under school closure (3,718.9).\n",
    "- **Trade-offs:** Highly compliance-dependent. Low cost and minimally disruptive.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. School Closure (2 weeks), Use Only as a Bridge, Not a Standalone Strategy\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Modeled effect:** Approximately 11,392 unique cases prevented (71,202 case-days / 6.25 days), but leaves 3,718.9 active cases at day 120, the worst day-120 outcome of all interventions.\n",
    "- **Critical caveat:** With the longer infectious period in these re-fitted parameters, the epidemic rebounds sharply after reopening. School closure without a sustained follow-on measure (masking or testing) is not recommended as a standalone strategy.\n",
    "- **Trade-offs:** High disruption to learning; disproportionate burden on students relying on campus resources.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4. Vaccine Interventions, Moderate Short-Term Impact\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Modeled effect (campaign):** Approximately 2,206 unique cases prevented (13,788 case-days / 6.25 days).\n",
    "- **Modeled effect (rollout):** Approximately 2,701 unique cases prevented (16,880 case-days / 6.25 days); spacing doses over three dates provides a modest advantage.\n",
    "- **Recommendation:** Deploy vaccine doses as quickly as possible since they are most valuable before the peak. Prioritize highest-contact subgroups such as dormitory residents, dining workers, and athletes.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Overall Recommendation\n",
    "\n",
    "Implement Testing and Quarantine as the primary intervention, paired immediately with universal masking. If testing capacity is limited initially, masking alone prevents approximately 10,904 cases without requiring infrastructure buildup. School closure should only be considered as a short bridge to buy time for testing capacity to scale, and must be paired with a sustained follow-on measure given the sharp rebound risk under this virus's infectious period.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Note: Unique cases prevented values are approximations computed as case-days prevented divided by the baseline infectious period (6.25 days). All projections also assume 100% immediate compliance; real-world benefits will be lower.*\n"
   ]
